ectedBy      = Norma Bailey\n |WrittenBy       = Elizabeth Higgins Clark\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|1|1}}\n |ShortSummary    = As Kat and Justin begin to compete Kat's disappointed that the low difficulty of their routine means they always finish well off the podium. Hoping to get a chance to compete nationally Kat makes a decision that prioritizes her career over her mental health. When Serena's father Reggie abruptly returns Mitch struggles with jealousy while Carol welcomes the news until she learns that Reggie plans to take Serena in full time.  \n |LineColor       = 1F1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 8\n |Title           = Hell Is Real\n |DirectedBy      = [[Jon Amiel]]\n |WrittenBy       = Paul Keables & Elizabeth Peterson\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|1|1}}\n |ShortSummary    = After weeks of not taking her meds Kat becomes manic and goes on a buying and partying spree that has devastating consequences for Justin and Marcus. Serena feels abandoned as Kat dodges her calls and Carol gets caught up helping Mandy when she goes into early labour.  \n |LineColor       = 1F1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 9\n |Title           = #1 Mom\n |DirectedBy      = Matt Hastings\n |WrittenBy       = Lara Olsen\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|1|1}}\n |ShortSummary    = After getting a call from Justin, Carol helps Kat to go back on her medication and lies to everyone that she has pneumonia. Now aware of Kat's secret, Justin and Marcus decide to keep quiet despite suffering harsh consequences for her behaviour. Despite Kat's desire to come clean about her disorder, Carol pressures Kat to stay silent about her mental illness.\n |LineColor       = 1F1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 10\n |Title           = Kiss & Cry\n |DirectedBy      = Jon Amiel\n |WrittenBy       = Samantha Stratton\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|1|1}}\n |ShortSummary    = Justin decides to end his personal and professional relationship with Kat only to change his mind at the last minute. The two head to Sectionals which is being held at the rink where Kat had her career altering injury. \nKat is distracted from the competition when Serena's behaviour leads her to once again suspect that Serena has been sexually assaulted by Mitch. \n |LineColor       = 1F1F1F\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nOn October 11, 2018, it was announced that [[Netflix]] had given the production a series order consisting of ten episodes. The series was created by Samantha Stratton who was also expected to serve as co-showrunner with Lara Olsen. Stratton and Olsen were also set to executive produce the series alongside Joby Harold and Tory Tunnell with Matt Schwartz serving as a co-executive producer. Production companies were slated to consist of Safehouse Pictures.<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\"/><ref name=\"SeriesOrder2\">{{cite web |last=Otterson |first=Joe |title=Netflix Orders Ice Skating Drama 'Spinning Out' Starring Emma Roberts |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/emma-roberts-netflix-spinning-out-1202977023/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=October 11, 2018 |date=October 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011205224/https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/emma-roberts-netflix-spinning-out-1202977023/ |archive-date=October 11, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"SeriesOrder3\">{{cite web |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |title=Emma Roberts to Star in Netflix Ice Skating Drama 'Spinning Out' |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/emma-roberts-star-netflix-ice-skating-drama-spinning-1151538 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=October 11, 2018 |date=October 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011214806/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/emma-roberts-star-netflix-ice-skating-drama-spinning-1151538 |archive-date=October 11, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On February 3, 2020, it was reported that the series was canceled after one season.<ref name=\"Canceled\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/spinning-out-canceled-netflix-one-season-1202850380/|title='Spinning Out' Canceled By Netflix After One Season|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=February 3, 2020|accessdate=February 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203234320/https://deadline.com/2020/02/spinning-out-canceled-netflix-one-season-1202850380/|archive-date=February 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nAlongside the series order announcement, it was confirmed that [[Emma Roberts]] would star in the series.<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\"/><ref name=\"SeriesOrder2\"/><ref name=\"SeriesOrder3\"/> On October 31, 2018, it was reported that Roberts had dropped out of the series, citing a scheduling conflict.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bryn Elise |first=Sandberg |title=Emma Roberts Drops Out of Netflix Figure Skating Drama 'Spinning Out' |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/emma-roberts-drops-netflix-figure-skating-drama-spinning-1156842 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=October 31, 2018 |date=October 31, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031234254/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/emma-roberts-drops-netflix-figure-skating-drama-spinning-1156842 |archive-date=October 31, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Otterson |first=Joe |title=Emma Roberts Exits Netflix Figure Skating Drama 'Spinning Out' |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/netflix-spinning-out-emma-roberts-1203016644/ |website=Variety |accessdate=October 31, 2018 |date=October 31, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181101004244/https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/netflix-spinning-out-emma-roberts-1203016644/ |archive-date=November 1, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |title=Emma Roberts Exits Netflix Drama Series 'Spinning Out', Role Is Being Recast |url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/emma-roberts-exits-netflix-figure-skating-drama-series-spinning-out-1202493390/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=October 31, 2018 |date=October 31, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031233240/https://deadline.com/2018/10/emma-roberts-exits-netflix-figure-skating-drama-series-spinning-out-1202493390/ |archive-date=October 31, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In December 2018, it was announced that [[Kaya Scodelario]] had been cast to replace Roberts in the role of Kat Baker. It was also reported that [[Willow Shields]], [[Evan Roderick]], [[Johnny Weir]], [[Sarah Wright Olsen]], [[Will Kemp (actor, born 1977)|Will Kemp]], Kaitlyn Leeb, Amanda Zhou, and Mitchell Edwards had been cast in series regular roles.<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |last2=Petski |first2=Denise |title=Kaya Scodelario To Star In Netflix's Figure Skating Drama Series 'Spinning Out' |url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/kaya-scodelario-star-spinning-out-figure-skating-drama-series-netflix-recasting-replaces-emma-roberts-1202519630/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=December 13, 2018 |date=December 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181213210725/https://deadline.com/2018/12/kaya-scodelario-star-spinning-out-figure-skating-drama-series-netflix-recasting-replaces-emma-roberts-1202519630/ |archive-date=December 13, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Otterson |first=Joe |title='Hunger Games' Alum Willow Shields Joins Netflix Drama Series 'Spinning Out' |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/hunger-games-willow-shields-spinning-out-netflix-1203090218/ |website=Variety |accessdate=December 14, 2018 |date=December 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215014109/https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/hunger-games-willow-shields-spinning-out-netflix-1203090218/ |archive-date=December 15, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Petski |first=Denise |title='Arrow's Evan Roderick Joins Netflix Drama Series 'Spinning Out' |url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/spinning-out-evan-roderick-cast-netflix-drama-series-kaya-scodelario-1202523201/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=December 19, 2018 |date=December 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219233521/https://deadline.com/2018/12/spinning-out-evan-roderick-cast-netflix-drama-series-kaya-scodelario-1202523201/ |archive-date=December 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Petski |first=Denise |title='Spinning Out': Johnny Weir, Sarah Wright Olsen, Will Kemp Among Six Cast In Netflix Drama Series |url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/spinning-out-johnny-weir-sarah-wright-olsen-will-kemp-cast-inetflix-drama-series-1202524024/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=December 20, 2018 |date=December 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220235105/https://deadline.com/2018/12/spinning-out-johnny-weir-sarah-wright-olsen-will-kemp-cast-inetflix-drama-series-1202524024/ |archive-date=December 20, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On January 16, 2019, it was reported that [[January Jones]] had joined the cast in a leading role.<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |title='Spinning Out': January Jones To Star In Netflix Figure Skating Drama Series |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/spinning-out-january-jones-cast-netflix-drama-series-1202536354/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=January 17, 2019 |date=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117035351/https://deadline.com/2019/01/spinning-out-january-jones-cast-netflix-drama-series-1202536354/ |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  On February 21, 2019, it was announced that Svetlana Efremova and Charlie Hewson had been cast in a series regular role and recurring capacity respectively.<ref>{{cite web |last=Pedersen |first=Erik |title='Spinning Out': Svetlana Efremova & Charlie Hewson Join Netflix Figure Skating Series |url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/spinning-out-svetlana-efremova-charlie-hewson-join-netflix-figure-skating-series-1202561496/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=February 21, 2019 |date=February 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222010550/https://deadline.com/2019/02/spinning-out-svetlana-efremova-charlie-hewson-join-netflix-figure-skating-series-1202561496/ |archive-date=February 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Figure skating doubles===\nA number of Canadian figure skaters served as skating doubles for the series' stars, including [[Michelle Long]] (singles skating) and [[Elizabeth Putnam (figure skater)|Elizabeth Putnam]] (singles and pairs skating) for Kaya Scodelario as Kat Baker, Kim Deguise L\u00e9veill\u00e9e (jumps) for Scodelario and Willow Shields as Serena Baker, and [[Dylan Moscovitch]] for [[Evan Roderick]] as Justin Davis.<ref name=\"seventeen\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/movies-tv/a30519103/pro-figure-skater-cameos-appearances-double-spinning-out/ |title=Meet All the Pro Figure Skaters Who Appeared on \"Spinning Out\" |last=Fuentes |first=Tamara |date=2020-01-15 |website=seventeen.com |access-date=2020-01-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200116092820/https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/movies-tv/a30519103/pro-figure-skater-cameos-appearances-double-spinning-out/ |archive-date=January 16, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Canadian pair team [[Evelyn Walsh]] and [[Trennt Michaud]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lfpress.com/sports/local-sports/walsh-and-michaud-spinning-into-skate-spotlight-this-season|title=London figure skater Evelyn Walsh spinning into spotlight this season|website=The London Free Press|first=Ryan|last=Pyette|date=September 4, 2019|accessdate=January 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101234636/https://lfpress.com/sports/local-sports/walsh-and-michaud-spinning-into-skate-spotlight-this-season|archive-date=January 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> served as doubles for Kat and Justin's pair elements. Other doubles include Lilika Zheng for Amanda Zhou as Jenn Yu, Emma Cullen for January Jones as Carol Baker, and [[Madeline Schizas]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehalton.com/community-story/9307534-silver-medal-leads-to-netflix-appearance-for-oakville-teen/|title=Silver medal leads to Netflix appearance for Oakville teen|website=InsideHalton.com|first=Herb|last=Garbutt|date=April 29, 2019|accessdate=January 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102161709/https://www.insidehalton.com/community-story/9307534-silver-medal-leads-to-netflix-appearance-for-oakville-teen/|archive-date=January 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> for Kaitlyn Leeb as Leah Starnes.\n\n===Filming===\nPrincipal photography for the series took place from January 28 to May 16, 2019 in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Current Productions {{!}} IATSE 873 |url=https://www.iatse873.com/current_productions |website=IATSE 873 |accessdate=January 29, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129064739/https://www.iatse873.com/current_productions |archivedate=January 29, 2019}}</ref> and filming at Blue Mountain Ski Resort in Ontario, Canada.\n\n==Reception==\n<!--AUDIENCE RECEPTION AND RATINGS: Do not include them! Wikipedia does not support user-generated content in its articles, and thus audience ratings cannot be included. Please refer to the talk page before proceeding to edit this section, and view the multiple discussions raised on the topic. No consensus has been formed to allow this article to differ from Wikipedia's guidelines and policies by including such content. Additions of audience ratings will be reverted.-->\nOn review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the series has an approval rating of 63% with an average rating of 6.5/10, based on 16 reviews. The website's critical consensus states, \"Though at times more melodramatic than meaningful, ''Spinning Out''{{'s}} campy, guilty-pleasure exterior hides a surprisingly thoughtful exploration of living with a mental illness.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/spinning_out/s01|title=Spinning Out: Season 1 (2020)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=January 25, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], it has a weighted average score of 47 out of 100, based 4 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/spinning-out/season-1|title=Spinning Out: Season 1|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRobyn Bahr of [[The Hollywood Reporter]] called it \"Uneven but mostly engrossing, it combines the unflinching class struggles of I, Tonya, the star-crossed romance of The Cutting Edge and the disability-as-tragedy goopiness of Ice Castles.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/spinning-review-1265351 |title= 'Spinning Out': TV Review |website= [[The Hollywood Reporter]] |first= Robyn |last= Bahr |date= December 31, 2019 |accessdate= January 19, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200116061409/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/spinning-review-1265351 |archive-date= January 16, 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> Caroline Framke  of [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] wrote \"The series has all the right ingredients for an addictive watch: a solid premise, some compelling actors, and some classic teen show tensions and rhythms in the earnest vein of \u201cDegrassi\u201d braiding it all together. But as the season plods towards its uneven finale, \u201cSpinning Out\u201d instead does exactly what its title promises instead of sticking the landing.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/reviews/spinning-out-netflix-dare-me-megan-abbott-review-1203450164/ |title=USA's 'Dare Me' and Netflix's 'Spinning Out': TV Review |website=Variety |first=Caroline |last=Framke |date=January 1, 2020 |accessdate=January 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114060151/https://variety.com/2020/tv/reviews/spinning-out-netflix-dare-me-megan-abbott-review-1203450164/ |archive-date=January 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Netflix title|80201590}}\n* {{IMDb title|9117054}}\n\n{{Netflix original ended series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spinning Out}}\n\n[[Category:2020 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2020 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2020s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:Bipolar disorder in fiction]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Figure skating on television]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Idaho]]\n", "name_user": "Franizzo", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spinning_Out"}
{"title_page": "Rally Trophy", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Rally Trophy\n| image = RallyTrophyBox.jpg\n| caption= European box art\n| developer = [[Bugbear Entertainment]]\n| publisher = [[JoWooD Productions]]\n| director = Janne Alanenp\u00e4\u00e4\n| designer = Janne Alanenp\u00e4\u00e4<br>Tatu Blomberg<br>Sami R\u00e4ih\u00e4\n| programmer = Tatu Blomberg\n| artist = Mikko Kautto<br>Hannu Leskinen<br>Sami R\u00e4ih\u00e4\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]]\n| released = November 20, 2001\n| genre = [[Racing video game|Racing]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Rally Trophy''''' is a 2001 historic PC rally simulation, created by [[Bugbear Entertainment]] and [[JoWood Productions]] for the [[Microsoft Windows]] operating system.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n|align = left\n|CGW = 4/5<ref name=\"metacritic\"/>\n|EuroG = 7/10<ref name=\"eurogamer\">{{cite web|last1=Taylor|first1=Martin|title=Rally Trophy|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/r_rtrophy|website=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network|accessdate=3 October 2017|date=27 January 2002}}</ref>\n|GSpot = 8.7/10<ref name=\"gamespot\">{{cite web|last1=Goble|first1=Gord|title=Rally Trophy Review|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/rally-trophy-review/1900-2830684/|website=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=3 October 2017|date=6 December 2001}}</ref>\n|IGN = 7.6/10<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web|last1=Polak|first1=Steve|title=Rally Trophy|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/05/29/rally-trophy|website=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|accessdate=3 October 2017|date=29 May 2002}}</ref>\n|rev1 = ''[[Pelit]]''\n|rev1Score = 90/100<ref name=\"pelit\">{{cite journal|last1=\u00c4\u00e4ril\u00e4|first1=Mika|title=Rally Trophy|date=November 2001|issue=11/2001|pages=32\u201335, 90}}</ref>\n|MC = 82/100<ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web|title=Rally Trophy Critic Reviews for PC|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/rally-trophy/critic-reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=3 October 2017}}</ref>\n|GR = 82%<ref name=\"gamerankings\">{{cite web|title=Rally Trophy for PC|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/531653-rally-trophy/index.html|website=[[GameRankings]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=3 October 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Rally Trophy'' received positive reviews upon its release. It holds an average of 82% and 82/100 on aggregate web sites [[GameRankings]] and [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"gamerankings\"/><ref name=\"metacritic\"/> The Finnish gaming magazine ''[[Pelit]]'' summarized that \"Rally Trophy sets the standard for all future driving games. The graphics are absolutely stunning and the lack of inspiring game modes is compensated by the sheer thrill of driving cars that behave uniquely and realistically. A must-have for all rally fans.<ref name=\"pelit\"/>\n\n[[IGN]] summarized that \"[Rally Trophy] is a superb game that offers an unusual alternative to the more technology packed offerings like [[Colin McRae Rally|McRae]] and [[Pro Rally]].\"<ref name=\"IGN\"/> Several critics compared the game to [[Grand Prix Legends]] including Pelit, IGN and [[GameSpot]].<ref name=\"pelit\"/><ref name=\"IGN\"/><ref name=\"gamespot\"/>\n\n''Rally Trophy'' was a nominee for ''[[PC Gamer US]]''{{'}}s \"2002 Best Racing Game\" award, which ultimately went to ''[[NASCAR Racing 2002 Season]]''.<ref name=pcgamerusawards2003>{{cite journal |date=March 2003 | title=The Ninth Annual ''PC Gamer'' Awards | volume=10 | number=3 | pages=48\u201350, 54, 58, 60, 66, 68, 70  | journal=[[PC Gamer US]] | author=Staff }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.mobygames.com/game/windows/rally-trophy ''Rally Trophy''] at [[MobyGames]]\n* {{dmoz|Games/Video_Games/Driving_and_Racing/Simulations/Rally_Trophy/}}\n\n[[Category:2001 video games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Xbox games]]\n[[Category:Off-road racing video games]]\n[[Category:Rally racing video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Finland]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Jonne Valtonen]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Finland]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Russia]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Windows-only games]]\n[[Category:JoWooD Entertainment games]]\n[[Category:Bugbear Entertainment games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Rally Trophy\n| image = RallyTrophyBox.jpg\n| caption= European box art\n| developer = [[Bugbear Entertainment]]\n| publisher = [[JoWooD Productions]]\n| director = Janne Alanenp\u00e4\u00e4\n| designer = Janne Alanenp\u00e4\u00e4<br>Tatu Blomberg<br>Sami R\u00e4ih\u00e4\n| programmer = Tatu Blomberg\n| artist = Mikko Kautto<br>Hannu Leskinen<br>Sami R\u00e4ih\u00e4\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]]\n| released = November 20, 2001\n| genre = [[Racing video game|Racing]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Rally Trophy''''' is a 2001 historic PC rally simulation, created by [[Bugbear Entertainment]] and [[JoWood Productions]] for the [[Microsoft Windows]] operating system.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n|CGW = 4/5<ref name=\"metacritic\"/>\n|EuroG = 7/10<ref name=\"eurogamer\">{{cite web|last1=Taylor|first1=Martin|title=Rally Trophy|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/r_rtrophy|website=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network|accessdate=3 October 2017|date=27 January 2002}}</ref>\n|GSpot = 8.7/10<ref name=\"gamespot\">{{cite web|last1=Goble|first1=Gord|title=Rally Trophy Review|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/rally-trophy-review/1900-2830684/|website=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=3 October 2017|date=6 December 2001}}</ref>\n|IGN = 7.6/10<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web|last1=Polak|first1=Steve|title=Rally Trophy|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/05/29/rally-trophy|website=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|accessdate=3 October 2017|date=29 May 2002}}</ref>\n|rev1 = ''[[Pelit]]''\n|rev1Score = 90/100<ref name=\"pelit\">{{cite journal|last1=\u00c4\u00e4ril\u00e4|first1=Mika|title=Rally Trophy|date=November 2001|issue=11/2001|pages=32\u201335, 90}}</ref>\n|MC = 82/100<ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web|title=Rally Trophy Critic Reviews for PC|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/rally-trophy/critic-reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=3 October 2017}}</ref>\n|GR = 82%<ref name=\"gamerankings\">{{cite web|title=Rally Trophy for PC|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/531653-rally-trophy/index.html|website=[[GameRankings]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=3 October 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Rally Trophy'' received positive reviews upon its release. It holds an average of 82% and 82/100 on aggregate web sites [[GameRankings]] and [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"gamerankings\"/><ref name=\"metacritic\"/> The Finnish gaming magazine ''[[Pelit]]'' summarized that \"Rally Trophy sets the standard for all future driving games. The graphics are absolutely stunning and the lack of inspiring game modes is compensated by the sheer thrill of driving cars that behave uniquely and realistically. A must-have for all rally fans.<ref name=\"pelit\"/>\n\n[[IGN]] summarized that \"[Rally Trophy] is a superb game that offers an unusual alternative to the more technology packed offerings like [[Colin McRae Rally|McRae]] and [[Pro Rally]].\"<ref name=\"IGN\"/> Several critics compared the game to [[Grand Prix Legends]] including Pelit, IGN and [[GameSpot]].<ref name=\"pelit\"/><ref name=\"IGN\"/><ref name=\"gamespot\"/>\n\n''Rally Trophy'' was a nominee for ''[[PC Gamer US]]''{{'}}s \"2002 Best Racing Game\" award, which ultimately went to ''[[NASCAR Racing 2002 Season]]''.<ref name=pcgamerusawards2003>{{cite journal |date=March 2003 | title=The Ninth Annual ''PC Gamer'' Awards | volume=10 | number=3 | pages=48\u201350, 54, 58, 60, 66, 68, 70  | journal=[[PC Gamer US]] | author=Staff }}</ref>\n\n