dth=33% |\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right;\"\n! style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:center; width:60%;\" | Date\n! style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:center; width:35%;\" | Population\n! style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:center; width:5%;\"  |\n|-\n| 1961 || 39.760 || \u00b9\n|-\n| 1970 || 46.018 || \u00b9\n|-\n| 31. December 1980 || 51.604 || &nbsp;\n|-\n| 31. December 1990 || 56.340 || &nbsp;\n|-\n| 31. December 2000 || 58.908 || &nbsp;\n|-\n| 30. June 2003 || 59.820 || &nbsp;\n|-\n| 30. September 2005 || 60.137 || &nbsp;\n|-\n| 30. September 2006 || 60.295 || &nbsp;\n|-\n| 30. September 2007 || 60.640 || &nbsp;\n|-\n| 31. December 2010 || 61.299 || &nbsp;\n|}\n|}\n\u00b9 Census results\n\n===Coat of arms===\n[[File:RO Riedergarten 2013-04.jpg|thumb|Riedergarten]]\n\nThe emblem of Rosenheim shows a white rose on a red background.  This may indicate the former arms of [[Wasserburg am Inn]] have returned, because Wasserburg ruled Rosenheim until 1247. The oldest known seal of Rosenheim was built in 1374 and already shows the rose, which has not changed since.  The only exception is a picture by [[Philipp Apian]], which was painted around the year 1568 and shows a border around the rose.<ref>Wappenverzeichnis: [http://www.ngw.nl/int/dld/r/rosenhei.htm http://www.ngw.nl/int/dld/r/rosenhei.htm]</ref>\n\nThere exists also a logo for Rosenheim, containing the same rose which is present on the coat of arms.\n\n== Landmarks and culture  ==\n[[File:Kultur und Kongresszentrum Rosenheim-1.jpg|thumb|Kultur- und Kongress-Zentrum]]\n\n=== Theater ===\nThe ''Kultur- und Kongresszentrum Rosenheim (KU'KO)'' (Culture and Congress Centre) was built on the site of the [[brine]] works, demolished in 1967. Inaugurated on October 2, 1982 as the town hall, now the Culture and Congress Centre Rosenheim has evolved over the years into a national event centre.  Today in the 3000-square-foot multipurpose building approximately 400 events are held annually.\n\n===Museums===\n[[File:Ludwigsplatz Rosenheim 3.jpg|thumb|right|Ludwigsplatz]]\n[[File:Mangfalleinm\u00fcndung in den Inn.jpg|thumb|Confluence of the river [[Mangfall]] in the river [[Inn (river)|Inn]]]]\nSince 1885, the {{ill|Mittertor|de}} has housed the Municipal Museum with a large collection (about 5000 exhibits) of the cultural history of the town and [[Rosenheim (district)|district of Rosenheim]], from the prehistory and early history and Roman times to the recent town history in the 20th century. It is one of the most important regional history collections in South East Upper Bavaria.\n\nThe Inn Museum houses the hydraulic engineering and marine technology collection of the Rosenheim Water Management Office and is located in the historic river master's ''Bruckbaustadel'' at the Inn Bridge.  With many original objects, the museum displays the Inn Shipping Company, the source of Rosenheim's prosperity in the Middle Ages, in the past centuries.  In addition, the museum provides facts about the river landscape and river engineering, geology, settlement history, marine engineering, bridge design and the development of waterways.\n\nThe ''Wood technology Museum'' was established in 1990 in the listed Ellmaierhaus. It is housed on the first floor, which is accessed via the so-called Jacob's ladder.  At more than 400 square meters of exhibition space displays this unique museum, which is closely related to the ''timber town of Rosenheim'' and its training centres for wood occupations, wood as a raw material, its importance and processing past and present.  The exhibition shows not only the end products, but also their production and the necessary tools.  Regular special exhibitions complete the offer of the ''Wood technology Museum''.\n\nThe Municipal Gallery of 1935-1937 was built by [[German Bestelmeyer]]. Every year, six art exhibitions are held here. In addition to contemporary art, also exhibitions of works from the 19th and 20th century are held.  A thematic focus is the art from the region and the [[Munich School]].\n\nThe ''{{ill|Lokschuppen Rosenheim|lt=Lokschuppen|de}}'' is an internationally renowned exhibition centre with annually changing exhibitions in the former railways round house.\n\nThe brine pump house is one of the few monuments in the town which recall time from 1810 to 1958 of Rosenheim's brine industry.<ref>Ludwig Gassner: ''Rosenheim und dessen Umgebung. F\u00fcr Fremde und Einheimische unter besonderer Ber\u00fccksichtigung des Heilbades Rosenheim''. Rosenheim 1865 ([https://books.google.de/books?id=A8lAAAAAcAAJ&pg=PP5 online]).</ref> As part of the National Exposition ''salt makes history'', the town renovated the historic, listed building and set up an exhibition room about Rosenheim's [[brine]] history. Admission is only possible with town guides or by agreement with the Metropolitan Museum.\n\nThe ''{{ill|Klepper Faltbootwerft|lt=Klepper|de||nl|Klepper (kano)}}'' museum houses various exhibits, on the one hand the history of the Klepper [[folding boat]], coats and tents.  On the other hand, it is also dedicated to the development of the company Klepper, who was once the biggest employer in Rosenheim.\n\n===Architecture ===\n[[File:Lokschuppen in Rosenheim05 klein Trux.jpg|thumb|Town Hall Rosenheim]]\nThe Mittertor (the sole survivor of five market gates) was the eastern gate of the market before 1350, which was then protected with a double ditch. Since the 15th century, it separated the interior from the exterior of the market served as a customs office. Until the 19th century it also contained several municipal facilities such as the [[Clerk (municipal official)|town clerk's]] office. After the great fire in 1641 the Rosenheim onion dome was built and later extended into a long building.  At its core is the Mittertor the oldest building in town.  On the fa\u00e7ade to the side of the square is the emblem of Louis Rosenheim, with the white rose against a red background. The [[coat of arms of Bavaria|Bavarian crest]] can also be seen here.\n[[File:Ludwigsplatz Fischbrunnen Rosenheim-1.jpg|thumb|right|Ludwigsplatz]]\n\nThe street ''M\u00fcnchener Strasse'' follows the ''Gillitzerblock'', that is also called \"small pedestrian zone.\"  Immediately apparent are the magnificently restored [[Gr\u00fcnderzeit]] fronts.  The name ''Gillitzerblock'' come from its builder Thomas Gillitzer.  At the end of the 19th century he obtained a relatively large area of land, for its day, and built 15 houses, including the Hotel ''Deutscher Kaiser''. Since the 1960s, the once solely Gr\u00fcnderzeit ensemble has been altered with new construction and renovations.  Only the fa\u00e7ades in ''M\u00fcnchener Strasse'' have been preserved and restored to the original.\n\nThe ''Quest-{{ill|Kunstm\u00fchle|de}}'' was built from 1855 to 1916 in several phases as industrial complexes. ''Kunstm\u00fchle'' was at these times the name for technically advanced mills - German ''Kunst'' means art. The mill was renovated in the 1990s and now serves as a restaurant and office space. The ''Quest-Kunstm\u00fchle'' Power station is located on the Mangfallkanal. The former mill houses the exhibition halls of the Rosenheim arts club. The approximately {{convert|200|m\u00b2|0|abbr=out}} upper floor holds exhibitions of contemporary artists, exchange exhibitions with other art associations and activities accompanying the exhibition.\n\nThe Rosenheim ballroom was built in the former Rosenheim Hofbr\u00e4us buildings. The hall with ballroom and vaulted cellar was built in 1878. It was renovated in 1994 and since 2001 has been used as an event space, with its many possible uses of the centre of the eastern town of Rosenheim.\n\nThe town's landmark is the gothic spire ({{convert|65|m|0|abbr=on}}) of the parish church St. Nikolaus ({{convert|1450|m|0|abbr=on}}) with its baroque [[onion dome]] ({{convert|1641|m|0|abbr=on}}).\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"float: right; width:30%\"\n|+ Sculptures in the ''Salingarten''\n! style=\"background:#CCDDEE;\" | Name || style=\"background:#CCDDEE;\" | Sculptor\n|-\n| Wasserrad || Josef Hamberger\n|-\n| Stehende || Rolf M\u00e4rkl\n|-\n| Liegende || {{ill|Marianne L\u00fcdicke|de}}\n|-\n| Mensch und Pferd || Prof. Heinrich Kirchner\n|-\n| Norne || Louise Stomps\n|-\n| Passantengruppe || Erika Maria Lankes\n|-\n| Stele || Alfred Regnat\n|}\n\n=== Parks ===\nThe ''Kunstwiese'' shows three-dimensional contemporary art works by artists from Rosenheim all year round.\n\nThe ''Riedergarten'' was created in 1729 as a private herb garden by Rosenheim pharmacist Johann Rieder. It was sold to the town in 1925 by physician Dr. Herman Rieder for use as a summer garden. In 2002 the garden was redesigned by the opening up of a previously culverted stream, adding a modern character.\n\nSince 1987 the ''Salingarten'', in front of the Culture and Congress Centre Ku'Ko, has been used as a sculpture garden. Large sculptures by important sculptors from Rosenheim and environment can be seen here.\n\n==Transport==\n\nThere are regular regional train connections to Munich and [[Salzburg]].\n\n==Notable residents==\n[[File:Franz Ferdinand (band) 2008.11.24 009.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Nick McCarthy]]]]\n\n*[[Nick McCarthy|Nicholas McCarthy]] (born 1974), English musician\n*[[Siegfried Fischbacher]]\n*[[Hermann G\u00f6ring]] (1893-1946), [[First world war|WWI]] [[Jagdgeschwader I (World War I)|flying ace]], German politician & senior member of [[NSDAP]] and convicted [[holocaust|war criminal]].\n*[[George Dzundza]] (born 1945), actor\n*[[Nadine Samonte]] (born 1988), actress\n*[[Hans-Ulrich Rudel]] (1916-1982), [[Junkers Ju 87|Stuka]] ace pilot, was not from Rosenheim, but he spent the last years of his life in the town.[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 102-13805, Hermann G\u00f6ring.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Hermann G\u00f6ring]]]]\n*[[Philipp Grubauer]], NHL goaltender\n*[[Tobias Schweinsteiger]] (born 1982), brother of [[Bastian Schweinsteiger]], former football player\n*[[Edmund Stoiber]], (born 1941), politician and jurist, former Minister President of Bavaria (CSU)\n*[[Mark Benecke]] (born 1970), biologist\n*[[Jupp Kapellmann]] (born 1949), former German footballer\n*[[Lars Bender]] (born 1989), footballer\n*[[Sven Bender]] (born 1989), footballer\n*[[Martin Tomczyk]] (born 1981), auto racing driver\n*[[Ray Manzarek]] (1939-2013), American musician, member of [[The Doors]]\n\n==Twin towns \u2013 sister cities==\nRosenheim is twinned with:<ref>{{cite web |title=St\u00e4dtepartnerschaften|url=https://www.rosenheim.de/stadt-buerger/wir-ueber-uns/staedtepartnerschaften.html|website=rosenheim.de|publisher=Rosenheim|language=de|accessdate=2019-11-28}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Lazise]], Italy, since 1974\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Brian\u00e7on]], France, since 1979\n*{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Ichikawa, Chiba|Ichikawa]], Japan, since 2004\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Out of Rosenheim]]\n* [[Rosenheim Poltergeist]]\n* [[Starbulls Rosenheim]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}} {{in lang|de}}\n* [https://www.fh-rosenheim.de/ Fachhochschule Rosenheim] {{in lang|de}}\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Rosenheim}}\n\n{{Germany_districts_bavaria}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rosenheim| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Bavaria]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Inn (river)]]\n[[Category:Holocaust locations in Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rosenheim"}
{"title_page": "Bruce Gibney", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Bruce Gibney\n| image         = File:Bruce_Gibney.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Bruce Cannon Gibney\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1976|02|16}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = American\n| occupation    = {{hlist | [[Venture capital]]ist | writer | lawyer}}\n| education    = [[Stanford University]] (BS)<br>[[University of California, Los Angeles]] (JD)\n| years_active  = \n| notable_works = ''A Generation of Sociopaths'' (2017)\n| website       = {{official URL}}\n}}\n\n'''Bruce Cannon Gibney''' (born February 16, 1976)<ref>[https://www.macleans.ca/culture/books/qa-a-gen-x-venture-capitalist-on-how-boomers-wrecked-america/ Q&A: A venture capitalist on how boomers wrecked America]</ref><ref>United States Public Records, 1970-2009 (California, 2002-2008)</ref> is an American writer and [[venture capital]]ist. He was one of the first investors at PayPal, and went on to work for PayPal founder [[Peter Thiel]]'s hedge fund Clarium and his venture capital company [[Founders Fund]]. His first book, ''A Generation of Sociopaths: How the Baby Boomers Betrayed America'', was published by [[Hachette (publisher)|Hachette]] in 2017.\n\n== Career ==\nGibney started investing when his [[Stanford University]] roommate [[Ken Howery]] co-founded [[PayPal]], the electronic payments company, and offered Gibney the chance to buy \"friends and family\" shares.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avcj.com/avcj/profile/53100/profile-founders-funds-bruce-gibney|title=Profile: Founders Fund's Bruce Gibney|website=avcj.com|publisher=Asian Venture Capital Journal|last1=Birkwood|first1=Susannah|accessdate=March 15, 2016}}</ref> After investing in PayPal, Gibney worked as a litigator but was soon hired by [[Peter Thiel]] after Thiel sold PayPal to [[eBay]] in 2002. Gibney worked at Thiel's [[hedge fund]], Clarium, until 2008, making occasional private investments including in [[Palantir Technologies]] in 2005 and later in [[DeepMind]], which was acquired by [[Google]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/jan/27/google-acquires-uk-artificial-intelligence-startup-deepmind|title=Google buys UK artificial intelligence startup Deepmind for \u00a3400m|last=Gibbs|first=Samuel|date=January 27, 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=January 12, 2017}}</ref> for around $450 million in 2014. He then moved to [[Founders Fund]], a venture capital fund started by Thiel. Thiel and Founders Fund were the earliest outside investors in Facebook, [[SpaceX]], and Palantir, and made other investments including in [[Airbnb|AirBnB]], [[Lyft]], [[Spotify]], and Stemcentrx, which [[AbbVie Inc.|AbbVie]] acquired for $10 billion a few years after Founders Fund's investment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/stemcentrx-acquired-by-abbvie-2016-4|title=A startup that just launched out of stealth a few months ago thinks it's found a way to treat cancer, and it just got bought for up to $10 billion|last=Ramsey|first=Lydia|date=April 28, 2016|website=businessinsider.com|publisher=Business Insider|access-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGibney wrote Founders Fund's controversial statement of ideology, ''What Happened to the Future?'', in 2011, which called for more aggressive investments in breakthrough technologies and became a widely cited article in the technology community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2011/11/28/no-death-no-taxes|title=No Death, No Taxes|last=Packer|first=George|date=November 28, 2011|website=newyorker.com|publisher=The New Yorker|access-date=November 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/founders-fund-the-future-2011-7|title=Facebook Investor Wants Flying Cars, Not 140 Characters|last=Gobry|first=Pascal-Emmanuel|date=July 30, 2011|website=businessinsider.com|publisher=Business Insider|access-date=December 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/429690/why-we-cant-solve-big-problems/|title=Why We Can't Solve Big Problems|last=Pontin|first=Jason|date=October 24, 2012|website=redhnologyreview.com|publisher=MIT|access-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2012/01/01/our-favorite-tech-long-reads-of-2011/|title=Our favorite tech long reads of 2011|last=Kelly|first=Heather|date=January 1, 2012|website=venturebeat.com|publisher=Venture Beat|access-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref> He also wrote other articles about start-ups and technology and lectured on these subjects, as well as Silicon Valley\u2019s \"libertarian problem\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inc.com/bruce-gibney/silicon-valleys-libertarian-problem.html|title=Silicon Valley's Libertarian Problem|first=Bruce|last=Gibney|date=August 13, 2012|website=Inc.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blakemasters.com/post/22271192791/peter-thiels-cs183-startup-class-8-notes-essay|title=CS 183: Class 8 Notes|last=Masters|first=Blake|date=May 2, 2012|website=blakemasters.com|publisher=Blake Masters|access-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inc.com/jessica-stillman/entrepreneurship-is-really-risky-right.html|title=Entrepreneurship Is Really Risky, Right?|last=Stillman|first=Jessica|date=February 1, 2012|website=inc.com|publisher=Inc|access-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hbr.org/2012/05/four-things-to-get-right-when|title=Four Things to Get Right When Starting a Company|last=Gibney, Howery|first=Bruce, Ken|date=May 9, 2012|website=hbr.org|publisher=Harcard Business Review|access-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hbr.org/2012/01/the-hbr-list-of-audacious-ideas|title=The HBR List of Audacious Ideas|last=|first=|date=January\u2013February 2012|website=hbr.org|publisher=Harvard Business Review|access-date=October 20, 2016}}</ref> Gibney left Founders Fund in December 2012.<ref>{{cite news |work= Tech Crunch |date= December 11, 2012 |author= Josh Constine |title= Founders Fund Partner Bruce Gibney Has Left The Firm |url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/12/11/founders-fund-bruce-gibney/ |accessdate= January 17, 2017 }}</ref> He continued to make personal investments, though he made few since 2015, stating in a January 2016 speech in [[Zurich]] that he believes start-ups are richly valued and expressing concern that too many start-ups are remaining private for too long, creating misalignment of incentives between executives and employees and investors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://worldwebforum.ch/display/B2/Speakers+2016|title=World Web Forum (2016) |date=|website=worldwebforum.com|publisher=World Web Forum|access-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== ''A Generation of Sociopaths'' ==\nGibney's first book, ''A Generation of Sociopaths: How the Baby Boomers Betrayed America'', linked American stagnation to the [[baby boomers]], characterizing the generation as being unusually prone to anti-social personality disorder, which Gibney believes unraveled the pro-social, pro-growth policies of mid-20th-century America.\n\nIn her review for ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction]]\u2013winning novelist [[Jane Smiley]] praised Gibney's \"wry, amusing style\", noting that \"he is at his best analysing the financial details of the various forms of national and environmental debt that our children and grandchildren will eventually have to pay.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/may/17/generation-sociopaths-review-trump-baby-boomers-ruined-world|title=A Generation of Sociopaths review \u2013 how Trump and other Baby Boomers ruined the world|last=Smiley|first=Jane|date=2017-05-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-08-19|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> She concluded that \"Gibney does convince me that those of us born between 1940 and 1965 (his definition) are a drag on the future.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/may/17/generation-sociopaths-review-trump-baby-boomers-ruined-world|title=A Generation of Sociopaths review \u2013 how Trump and other Baby Boomers ruined the world|last=Smiley|first=Jane|date=2017-05-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-08-19|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In her summer book list review for the ''[[Financial Times]]'', [[Merryn Somerset Webb]] called ''A Generation of Sociopaths'' \"convincing stuff. Look around you in the UK and you will see hints of the same thing: our own boomers aren't rushing to give up any of their goodies for the young. Anyone in any doubt need only ask a dinner party of them how they feel about capital gains tax on primary residences or worse, asking pensioners to help finance their own medical care by paying national insurance.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/8dcceb14-67b4-11e7-9a66-93fb352ba1fe|title=We're going to hell in a handcart- but whose fault is it?|last=|first=|date=July 14, 2017|website=Financial Times|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2017-08-19}}</ref>\n\nIn his review in ''[[The Washington Post]]'', [[Dana Milbank]] wrote that although Gibney overstated his case concerning the Boomers, \"The core of Gibney's argument, that the boomers are guilty of 'generational plunder,' is spot-on.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/if-americas-messed-up-blame-it-on-the-boomers/2017/03/09/a6ccce16-eef8-11e6-b4ff-ac2cf509efe5_story.html|title=If America\u2019s messed up, blame it on the boomers|last=Milbank|first=Dana|date=2017-03-09|work=The Washington Post|access-date=2017-03-10|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> ''[[Booklist]]'' described the book as \"informative, provocative, and entertaining\" in its review.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.booklistonline.com/A-Generation-of-Sociopaths-How-the-Baby-Boomers-Betrayed-America-Bruce-Cannon-Gibney/pid=8512314|title=Booklist Review: A Generation of Sociopaths|first=Raymond|last=Pun |work=Booklist Online|date=January 9, 2017|access-date=2017-03-02}}</ref> ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' called the book an \"endless, broadest-possible-brush harangue\" that has \"some points, all of which would have been better made without assigning damning agency to them: of course health care has to be restructured, and of course taxes have to be raised if the nation is to escape insolvency. His prescriptions on those fronts are sound, though some are surely controversial.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/bruce-cannon-gibney/a-generation-of-sociopaths/|title=Kirkus Review: A Generation of Sociopaths|work=Kirkus Reviews|date=January 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gibney, Bruce}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American venture capitalists]]\n[[Category:Litigators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:PayPal people]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:UCLA School of Law alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Bruce Gibney\n| image         = File:Bruce_Gibney.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Bruce Cannon Gibney\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1976|02|16}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = American\n| occupation    = {{hlist | [[Venture capital]]ist | writer | lawyer}}\n| education    = [[Stanford University]] (BS)<br>[[University of California, Los Angeles]] (JD)\n| years_active  = \n| notable_works = ''A Generation of Sociopaths'' (2017)\n| website       = {{official URL}}\n}}\n\n'''Bruce Cannon Gibney''' (born February 16, 1976)<ref>[https://www.macleans.ca/culture/books/qa-a-gen-x-venture-capitalist-on-how-boomers-wrecked-america/ Q&A: A venture capitalist on how boomers wrecked America]</ref><ref>United States Public Records, 1970-2009 (California, 2002-2008)</ref> is an American writer and [[venture capital]]ist. He was one of the first investors at PayPal, and went on to work for PayPal founder [[Peter Thiel]]'s hedge fund Clarium and his venture capital company [[Founders Fund]]. His first book, ''A Generation of Sociopaths: How the Baby Boomers Betrayed America'', was published by [[Hachette (publisher)|Hachette]] in 2017.\n\n== Career ==\nGibney started investing when his [[Stanford University]] roommate [[Ken Howery]] co-founded [[PayPal]], the electronic payments company, and offered Gibney the chance to buy \"friends and family\" shares.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avcj.com/avcj/profile/53100/profile-founders-funds-bruce-gibney|title=Profile: Founders Fund's Bruce Gibney|website=avcj.com|publisher=Asian Venture Capital Journal|last1=Birkwood|first1=Susannah|accessdate=March 15, 2016}}</ref> After investing in PayPal, Gibney worked as a litigator but was soon hired by [[Peter Thiel]] after Thiel sold PayPal to [[eBay]] in 2002. Gibney worked at Thiel's [[hedge fund]], Clarium, until 2008, making occasional private investments including in [[Palantir Technologies]] in 2005 and later in [[DeepMind]], which was acquired by [[Google]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/jan/27/google-acquires-uk-artificial-intelligence-startup-deepmind|title=Google buys UK artificial intelligence startup Deepmind for \u00a3400m|last=Gibbs|first=Samuel|date=January 27, 2014||newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=January 12, 2017}}</ref> for around $450 million in 2014. He then moved to [[Founders Fund]], a venture capital fund started by Thiel. Thiel and Founders Fund were the earliest outside investors in Facebook, [[SpaceX]], and Palantir, and made other investments including in [[Airbnb|AirBnB]], [[Lyft]], [[Spotify]], and Stemcentrx, which [[AbbVie Inc.|AbbVie]] acquired for $10 billion a few years after Founders Fund's investment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/stemcentrx-acquired-by-abbvie-2016-4|title=A startup that just launched out of stealth a few months ago thinks it's found a way to treat cancer, and it just got bought for up to $10 billion|last=Ramsey|first=Lydia|date=April 28, 2016|website=businessinsider.com|publisher=Business Insider|access-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGibney wrote Founders Fund's controversial statement of ideology, ''What Happened to the Future?'', in 2011, which called for more aggressive investments in breakthrough technologies and became a widely cited article in the technology community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2011/11/28/no-death-no-taxes|title=No Death, No Taxes|last=Packer|first=George|date=November 28, 2011|website=newyorker.com|publisher=The New Yorker|access-date=November 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/founders-fund-the-future-2011-7|title=Facebook Investor Wants Flying Cars, Not 140 Characters|last=Gobry|first=Pascal-Emmanuel|date=July 30, 2011|website=businessinsider.com|publisher=Business Insider|access-date=December 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/429690/why-we-cant-solve-big-problems/|title=Why We Can't Solve Big Problems|last=Pontin|first=Jason|date=October 24, 2012|website=redhnologyreview.com|publisher=MIT|access-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2012/01/01/our-favorite-tech-long-reads-of-2011/|title=Our favorite tech long reads of 2011|last=Kelly|first=Heather|date=January 1, 2012|website=venturebeat.com|publisher=Venture Beat|access-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref> He also wrote other articles about start-ups and technology and lectured on these subjects, as well as Silicon Valley\u2019s \"libertarian problem\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inc.com/bruce-gibney/silicon-valleys-libertarian-problem.html|title=Silicon Valley's Libertarian Problem|first=Bruce|last=Gibney|date=August 13, 2012|website=Inc.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blakemasters.com/post/22271192791/peter-thiels-cs183-startup-class-8-notes-essay|title=CS 183: Class 8 Notes|last=Masters|first=Blake|date=May 2, 2012|website=blakemasters.com|publisher=Blake Masters|access-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inc.com/jessica-stillman/entrepreneurship-is-really-risky-right.html|title=Entrepreneurship Is Really Risky, Right?|last=Stillman|first=Jessica|date=February 1, 2012|website=inc.com|publisher=Inc|access-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hbr.org/2012/05/four-things-to-get-right-when|title=Four Things to Get Right When Starting a Company|last=Gibney, Howery|first=Bruce, Ken|date=May 9, 2012|website=hbr.org|publisher=Harcard Business Review|access-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hbr.org/2012/01/the-hbr-list-of-audacious-ideas|title=The HBR List of Audacious Ideas|last=|first=|date=January\u2013February 2012|website=hbr.org|publisher=Harvard Business Review|access-date=October 20, 2016}}</ref> Gibney left Founders Fund in December 2012.<ref>{{cite news |work= Tech Crunch |date= December 11, 2012 |author= Josh Constine |title= Founders Fund Partner Bruce Gibney Has Left The Firm |url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/12/11/founders-fund-bruce-gibney/ |accessdate= January 17, 2017 }}</ref> He continued to make personal investments, though he made few since 2015, stating in a January 2016 speech in [[Zurich]] that he believes start-ups are richly valued and expressing concern that too many start-ups are remaining private for too long, creating misalignment of incentives between executives and employees and investors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://worldwebforum.ch/display/B2/Speakers+2016|title=World Web Forum (2016) |date=|website=worldwebforum.com|publisher=World Web Forum|access-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== ''A Generation of Sociopaths'' ==\nGibney's first book, ''A Generation of Sociopaths: How the Baby Boomers Betrayed America'', linked American stagnation to the [[baby boomers]], characterizing the generation as being unusually prone to anti-social personality disorder, which Gibney believes unraveled the pro-social, pro-growth policies of mid-20th-century America.\n\nIn her review for ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction]]\u2013winning novelist [[Jane Smiley]] praised Gibney's \"wry, amusing style\", noting that \"he is at his best analysing the financial details of the various forms of national and environmental debt that our children and grandchildren will eventually have to pay.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/may/17/generation-sociopaths-review-trump-baby-boomers-ruined-world|title=A Generation of Sociopaths review \u2013 how Trump and other Baby Boomers ruined the world|last=Smiley|first=Jane|date=2017-05-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-08-19|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> She concluded that \"Gibney does convince me that those of us born between 1940 and 1965 (his definition) are a drag on the future.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/may/17/generation-sociopaths-review-trump-baby-boomers-ruined-world|title=A Generation of Sociopaths review \u2013 how Trump and other Baby Boomers ruined the world|last=Smiley|first=Jane|date=2017-05-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-08-19|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In her summer book list review for the ''[[Financial Times]]'', [[Merryn Somerset Webb]] called ''A Generation of Sociopaths'' \"convincing stuff. Look around you in the UK and you will see hints of the same thing: our own boomers aren't rushing to give up any of their goodies for the young. Anyone in any doubt need only ask a dinner party of them how they feel about capital gains tax on primary residences or worse, asking pensioners to help finance their own medical care by paying national insurance.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/8dcceb14-67b4-11e7-9a66-93fb352ba1fe|title=We're going to hell in a handcart- but whose fault is it?|last=|first=|date=July 14, 2017|website=Financial Times|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2017-08-19}}</ref>\n\nIn his review in ''[[The Washington Post]]'', [[Dana Milbank]] wrote that although Gibney overstated his case concerning the Boomers, \"The core of Gibney's argument, that the boomers are guilty of 'generational plunder,' is spot-on.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/if-americas-messed-up-blame-it-on-the-boomers/2017/03/09/a6ccce16-eef8-11e6-b4ff-ac2cf509efe5_story.html|title=If America\u2019s messed up, blame it on the boomers|last=Milbank|first=Dana|date=2017-03-09|work=The Washington Post|access-date=2017-03-10|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> ''[[Booklist]]'' described the book as \"informative, provocative, and entertaining\" in its review.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.booklistonline.com/A-Generation-of-Sociopaths-How-the-Baby-Boomers-Betrayed-America-Bruce-Cannon-Gibney/pid=8512314|title=Booklist Review: A Generation of Sociopaths|first=Raymond|last=Pun |work=Booklist Online|date=January 9, 2017|access-date=2017-03-02}}</ref> ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' called the book an \"endless, broadest-possible-brush harangue\" that has \"some points, all of which would have been better made without assigning damning agency to them: of course health care has to be restructured, and of course taxes have to be raised if the nation is to escape insolvency. His prescriptions on those fronts are sound, though some are surely controversial.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/bruce-cannon-gibney/a-generation-of-sociopaths/|title=Kirkus Review: A Generation of Sociopaths|work=Kirkus Reviews|date=January 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gibney, Bruce}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American venture capitalists]]\n[[Category:Litigators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:PayPal people]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:UCLA School of Law alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bruce_Gibney"}
